<h2 class="nounderline"><a name="maincontentlink">Persons with Disabilities (Equal Opportunities, Protection of Rights and Full Participation) Act, 1995 (PWD Act)</a></h2>

<p>
<a href="http://socialwelfare.delhigovt.nic.in/disabilityact.htm">Read the entire act</a>
</p>
<h3>Summary</h3>
<p>
Passed in 1995, the Persons with Disabilities Act, covers the following disability areas and are defined by the act as follows:
</p>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Blindness</strong>- Total absence of sight or
	<ul>
		<li>Visual acuity not exceeding 6/60 or 20/200 (Snellen chart) in the better eye with corrective lenses.</li>
		<li>Limited field of vision subtending an angle of 20 degrees or worse</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><strong>Low Vision</strong>- which includes the visual capacity to execute a task with appropriate devices.</li>
	<li><strong>Leprosy cured</strong>- This involves three stages.
	<ul>
		<li>A person cured of leprosy but has loss of sensation in hands &amp; feet, and paresis in the eyes.</li>
		<li>Manifests deformity and paresis but has sufficient mobility in hands and feet to engage in normal economic activity.</li>
		<li>Severe physical deformity coupled with advancement in age preventing the undertaking of gainful employment.</li>
	</ul></li>
	<li><strong>Loco motor disability</strong>- This implies disability of the bones, joints or muscles resulting in substantial restriction of limb movements or any form of cerebral palsy.</li>
	<li><strong>Hearing impairment</strong>- Loss of 60 decibels or more in the better ear.</li>
	<li><strong>Mental retardation</strong>- means a condition of arrested of incomplete development of the mind which is specially characterized by sub normality of intelligence.</li>
	<li><strong>Mental Illness</strong>- Implies any mental disorder other than mental retardation.</li>
</ul>
<p>
The person with a disability should be certified as having no less than 40 
percent of any disability as certified by a medical authority.
</p>
<p>
The Act grants protection of rights, equal opportunities, and full participation by appropriate governments and local authorities, in the following areas:
</p>
<h3>Education</h3>
<ul>
	<li>Every child with a disability is entitled to free education up in an appropriate environment up to the age of 18 years.</li>
	<li>The government will promote setting up of special schools in the government and private sector.</li>
	<li>It will promote the integration of students with disabilities in mainstream schools.</li>
	<li>It will provide opportunities for vocational training for children with disabilities.</li>
	<li>Children with disabilities having studied up to class five can continue their education as part-time students through functional literacy programmes or through open schools or universities.</li>
	<li>Every child with a disability should be provided with special books and equipment needed for his or her education, free of cost.</li>
	<li>All government educational institutions and aided institutions will reserve up to three percent 
	of its seats for persons with disabilities.</li>
	<li>State governments will make suitable modifications in the examination system to eliminate purely mathematical questions for students with visual impairments.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Public Accessibility</h3>
<ul>
	<li>There will be no discrimination of persons with disabilities in transport facilities, traffic signals or in built environments.</li>
	<li>State governments within the limit of their economic capacities will install auditory signals at red lights and have barrier free environments to ensure access to all.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Employment</h3>
<ul>
	<li>The act proposes to identify posts which can be reserved for persons with blindness or low vision, persons with hearing impairments and persons with locomotor disabilities or cerebral palsy. There will be no more than one percent reservation of jobs for each of the above mentioned categories.</li>
	<li>Incentives are also to be given to employers to ensure that five percent of the workforce consists of persons with disabilities.</li>
	<li>No establishment can reduce in rank, an employee who acquires a disability during service. If an employee is not suitable for his or her current post 
	after acquiring a disability, that employee can be shifted to another post within the same pay scale or service benefit.</li>
	<li>No promotion can be denied on the grounds of a disability.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Health</h3>
<ul>
	<li>State governments are to promote methods to prevent disabilities, screen all children once a year to identify those "at-risk", and create awareness through media.</li>
	<li>State governments will promote and sponsor research in the areas of prevention, rehabilitation, assistive devices, job identification and onsite modification in offices and factories.</li>
	<li>Recognition of institutions for persons with disabilities will be regulated by state governments.</li>
	<li>The act emphasized the adoption of various initiatives under "Government Schemes and Individual Benefits/Concessions for Persons with disabilities."</li>
</ul>
